_⚠️ Potential issue_ | _🟡 Minor_ | _⚡ Quick win_

**Treat `null` runPolicy as missing during normalization.**

At Line 44, only `undefined` is treated as “absent.” Persisted JSON can contain `runPolicy: null`, which would skip migration and leave state without a usable policy object.



<details>
<summary>Suggested patch</summary>

```diff
 export function normalizeRunPolicy(
   state: DeliveryState,
   config: ResolvedOrchestratorConfig,
 ): DeliveryState {
-  if (state.runPolicy !== undefined) {
+  if (state.runPolicy !== undefined && state.runPolicy !== null) {
     return state;
   }

   return { ...state, runPolicy: deriveRunPolicyFromConfig(config) };
 }
```
</details>

<!-- suggestion_start -->

<details>
<summary>📝 Committable suggestion</summary>

> ‼️ **IMPORTANT**
> Carefully review the code before committing. Ensure that it accurately replaces the highlighted code, contains no missing lines, and has no issues with indentation. Thoroughly test & benchmark the code to ensure it meets the requirements.

```suggestion
export function normalizeRunPolicy(
  state: DeliveryState,
  config: ResolvedOrchestratorConfig,
): DeliveryState {
  if (state.runPolicy !== undefined && state.runPolicy !== null) {
    return state;
  }

  return { ...state, runPolicy: deriveRunPolicyFromConfig(config) };
}
```

</details>

<!-- suggestion_end -->

<details>
<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>

```
Verify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the
rest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.

In `@tools/delivery/state.ts` around lines 44 - 45, The current guard returns
early when state.runPolicy !== undefined, which treats null as present; update
the normalization logic in tools/delivery/state.ts to treat both null and
undefined as missing (e.g., check state.runPolicy != null or explicitly check
for !== null && !== undefined) so that a persisted runPolicy: null triggers the
migration/creation of a usable policy object; change the early-return condition
around state.runPolicy (the block starting with if (state.runPolicy !==
undefined) { return state; }) to only return when runPolicy is actually a valid
policy object instead of null.
```

